several books
about teachers and education,
and is with

23:26.972 --> 23:32.278 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the conservative think tank the
American Enterprise
Institute, where Betsy DeVos is
a board member.

23:32.311 --> 23:33.779 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Welcome to you both.

23:33.812 --> 23:35.180 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RANDI WEINGARTEN, President,
American Federation
of Teachers: Thank you.

23:35.214 --> 23:36.448 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Randi
Weingarten, I would
like to start to you.

23:36.482 --> 23:37.516 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RANDI WEINGARTEN: And Rick and I
are good
friends, by the way.

23:37.549 --> 23:38.751 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: And you two
are good friends.

23:38.784 --> 23:40.352 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's good to get out there.

23:40.386 --> 23:42.321 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Randi, you heard Betsy DeVos.

23:42.354 --> 23:44.823 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She said she's not an enemy of
public schools.

23:44.857 --> 23:46.792 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, what concerns you?

23:46.825 --> 23:52.865 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RANDI WEINGARTEN: Well, that is
clearly contradictory
to the 30 years of evidence,
where she has

23:52.898 --> 23:57.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
called public schools dead ends,
where she
has said that they should be
retired, where

23:57.336 --> 24:04.443 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
she ran a campaign against
Republicans and
Democrats alike in Detroit where
her hashtag

24:04.476 --> 24:07.346 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
was #endDPS, end Detroit Public
Schools.

24:07.379 --> 24:15.020 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I assume that she's saying
that now because
suburban voters, rural voters,
Democrats,

24:15.054 --> 24:20.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Republicans alike, 90 percent of
the kids
in America attend public
schools.

24:20.225 --> 24:22.928 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But her record speaks volumes.

24:22.961 --> 24:28.567 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what we're concerned about
is that record,
because, in Michigan, as you
said, for the

24:28.600 --> 24:35.240 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
last 25 years, she has worked to
dismantle,
destabilize and defund public
schools at the

24:35.274 --> 24:43.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
very same time as she's worked
to shield for-profit
charters from any kind of
accountability.

24:44.016 --> 24:46.251 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And those schools have done very
badly.

24:46.285 --> 24:51.357 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And the public schools,
particularly for black
and brown children, have been
very destabilized

24:51.390 --> 24:55.060 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in places like Flint, Detroit,
Ecore (ph)
and other places.

24:55.094 --> 24:57.996 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Rick Hess, you
have heard
these criticisms before, I know.

24:58.030 --> 25:03.469 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What is -- you believe her
record indicates
that she ought to be the
secretary of education.

25:03.502 --> 25:05.270 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What do you like about her?

25:05.304 --> 25:06.105 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FREDERICK HESS, Director of
Education Policy
Studies, American Enterprise
Institute: You

25:06.138 --> 25:07.940 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
know, I think she's a smart
woman.

25:07.973 --> 25:09.141 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
She's a thoughtful woman.

25:09.174 --> 25:12.244 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She's spent three decades as an
educational
advocate.

25:12.277 --> 25:17.049 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, it's true that she -- her
vision about
how you advocate to serve all
children well

25:17.082 --> 25:21.153 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is very different from Randi's
or the AFT's.

25:21.186 --> 25:22.488 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Betsy works from a different
premise.

25:22.521 --> 25:25.157 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The premise is that these
dollars do not belong
to systems.

25:25.190 --> 25:26.759 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They do not belong to
bureaucracies.

25:26.792 --> 25:30.896 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They do not belong to state
education agencies
and local education agencies.

25:30.929 --> 25:36.802 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These are -- we spend $650
billion, $700 billion
a year to educate all of our
nation's children,

25:36.835 --> 25:38.704 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
50 million-odd kids.

25:38.737 --> 25:43.041 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If those families think those
children are
better served in a traditional
district school

25:43.075 --> 25:49.681 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or a charter school or a private
option, Betsy's
philosophy is that we ought to
regard it as

25:49.715 --> 25:53.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
an opportunity to make sure that
each of these
families and each of these kids
is better

25:53.452 --> 25:55.454 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
served.

25:55.487 --> 26:00.058 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't understand why anybody
would necessarily
view any of that as
anti-education or anti-public

26:00.092 --> 26:01.059 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
education.

26:01.093 --> 26:02.261 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Well, Randi,
you heard this.

26:02.294 --> 26:03.529 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What do you make of that
argument?

26:03.562 --> 26:05.397 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
RANDI WEINGARTEN: Right.

26:05.431 --> 26:12.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, at the end of the day, what
Rick is ignoring
is that 23 states have actually
reduced their

26:12.104 --> 26:15.841 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
investment in public education
since 2008.

26:15.874 --> 26:21.747 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what has happened here is
that what DeVos
advocates is a zero sum game,
take the money

26:21.780 --> 26:22.748 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
from public schools.

26:22.781 --> 26:24.917 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, what's happened in Detroit?

26:24.950 --> 26:26.985 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Kids have huge class sizes.

26:27.019 --> 26:28.687 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The buildings are decrepit.

26:28.720 --> 26:32.458 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The books that they use are from
the '60s
or the '70s.

26:32.491 --> 26:37.896 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, what happens is that they
don't have a
real viable experience.

26:37.930 --> 26:42.868 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, at the same time, what has
happened is
that there's been private money
that's gone

26:42.901 --> 26:49.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
into charters and gone into
vouchers to actually
overpromise parents things that
they ultimately

26:49.475 --> 26:51.143 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
don't get.

26:51.176 --> 26:55.514 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The place that has the choice
are the schools,
not the parents.

26:55.547 --> 26:58.984 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the point I'm trying to make
is that look
at the record.

26:59.017 --> 27:02.321 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The record in terms of vouchers
-- we have
had vouchers for 25 years.

27:02.354 --> 27:04.623 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They don't do very well for
kids.

27:04.656 --> 27:08.694 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the record in terms of the
for-profit
charters is that the for-profits
have made

27:08.727 --> 27:11.296 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a lot of money, but kids have
suffered.

27:11.330 --> 27:16.702 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, why are we in the midst of
destabilizing,
destabilizing, destabilizing, as
opposed to

27:16.735 --> 27:19.838 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
rolling up our sleeves and
actually doing
what works?

27:19.872 --> 27:24.843 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have to help every child have
a safe, welcoming
neighborhood public school.

27:24.877 --> 27:26.945 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Parents want other option,
that's their right.

27:26.979 --> 27:34.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we have a responsibility to
help kids
have qualified, high-quality
neighborhood

27:34.453 --> 27:36.255 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
public schools.

27:36.288 --> 27:38.223 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Rick, one of
the arguments
that often is made here, it
seems like there

27:38.257 --> 27:41.827 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is a tension between autonomy
and accountability.

27:41.860 --> 27:44.963 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Everyone wants autonomy, so that
schools can
innovate and do what they want
to do, but

27:44.997 --> 27:48.467 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
there should also be
accountability, so that,
if teachers are not doing a
great job, that

27:48.500 --> 27:50.302 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
somehow we can hold them
accountability.

27:50.335 --> 27:55.474 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DeVos has been very strong on
autonomy for
schools, but it seems like her
record indicates

27:55.507 --> 27:59.111 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
she's much less interested in
holding those
schools accountable when they
don't perform.

27:59.144 --> 28:01.446 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
RICK HESS: So, I think she's
mixed on accountability.

28:01.480 --> 28:06.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jeb Bush, who is probably the
high priest
of Republican educational
accountability,

28:06.852 --> 28:10.389 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
made an incredibly strong
statement on her
behalf in the last day or two.

28:10.422 --> 28:13.091 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She's been on the board of his
Foundation
for Educational Excellence.

28:13.125 --> 28:16.128 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She's supported calls for high
standards.

28:16.161 --> 28:20.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think you're right that
there is mixed
feelings, certainly on the
conservative side

28:20.933 --> 28:27.472 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the spectrum, about how much
we want to
have simple, centralized
measures determine

28:27.506 --> 28:29.408 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
whether or not a school is good
for a kid.

28:29.441 --> 28:34.580 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's interesting to hear, you
know, Randi
talking about this, because the
AFT also has,

28:34.613 --> 28:39.985 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, voiced concerns about
overreliance
on simple reading and math
scores as the be-all

28:40.018 --> 28:42.821 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and end-all for deciding whether
schools are
doing a good job.

28:42.854 --> 28:48.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And yet, when we talk about
educational accountability,
simply because it is so complex
to try to

28:48.860 --> 28:55.968 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
hold accountable 100,000
schools, because
we have so few kind of good,
objective measures,

28:56.001 --> 28:59.771 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it often that winds up putting
more and more
weight on reading and math
scores.

28:59.805 --> 29:04.476 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think, for me, part of the
promise of
school choice is that if
educators can create

29:04.509 --> 29:10.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a school that families want to
send their
kid to, and looking at the test
data and looking

29:10.048 --> 29:14.820 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at other metrics of achievement,
families
think that this school is best
for their kids,

29:14.853 --> 29:20.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I guess I'm uncomfortable with
the idea that
we should -- that we should
religiously try

29:20.492 --> 29:23.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to deny families a school that
they think
is going to be best for their
kid.

29:23.462 --> 29:32.571 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
Randi Weingarten,
Rick Hess, thank you both very
much.

