40:14.479 --> 40:16.247 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Like, you're president of the
United States.

40:16.281 --> 40:21.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is true that the majority of
people who
you serve, who you represent,
that's not the

40:22.020 --> 40:23.755 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
South Side of Chicago anymore.

40:23.788 --> 40:28.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: One of the first
tests came
just months into Mr. Obama's
first term, when

40:28.459 --> 40:34.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a white police officer arrested
black Harvard
Professor Henry Louis Gates
trying to get

40:34.666 --> 40:35.767 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
into his own home.

40:35.800 --> 40:41.372 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA: The Cambridge
police acted stupidly.

40:41.406 --> 40:48.446 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What I think we know, separate
and apart from
this incident, is that there is
a long history

40:48.479 --> 40:55.420 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
in this country of
African-Americans and Latinos
being stopped by law enforcement
disproportionately.

40:55.453 --> 41:00.591 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: After backlash
from the law
enforcement community, the
president said

41:00.625 --> 41:02.427 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
he had overreacted.

41:02.460 --> 41:07.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He invited Gates and the officer
who had arrested
him to the White House for what
would become

41:07.565 --> 41:09.567 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
known as the beer summit.

41:09.600 --> 41:15.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The president experienced
unusual vitriol
from his opponents, including an
outburst

41:15.373 --> 41:20.945 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
from South Carolina
Representative Joe Wilson
that members of both parties
called disrespectful.

41:20.978 --> 41:21.946 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

41:21.979 --> 41:24.816 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOE WILSON (R), South Carolina:
You lie!

41:24.849 --> 41:26.584 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
(BOOING)

41:26.617 --> 41:30.154 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: For the remainder
of his first
term, the president rarely used
the bully

41:30.188 --> 41:32.357 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
pulpit to talk about race.

41:32.390 --> 41:37.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He focused instead on broader
issues, like
the economy and reforming the
nation's health

41:37.729 --> 41:40.031 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
care system.

41:40.064 --> 41:45.236 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the president's domestic
record in his
second term would be largely
defined by a

41:45.269 --> 41:49.407 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
series of events that
spotlighted racial tensions.

41:49.440 --> 41:56.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In 2012, when neighborhood watch
volunteer
George Zimmerman shot and killed
Trayvon Martin,

41:56.280 --> 42:02.820 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
an unarmed black teenager, the
president spoke
out in a surprisingly personal
way.

42:02.854 --> 42:04.622 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Valerie Jarrett was with him
just beforehand.

42:04.655 --> 42:08.593 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VALERIE JARRETT: And I was in
the Oval Office
with a couple of other senior
staff.

42:08.626 --> 42:14.465 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And he said to us, in an
extraordinarily emotional
way: "I want to talk about this
because, if

42:14.499 --> 42:16.401 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I had a son, he would look like
Trayvon."

42:16.434 --> 42:23.141 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA: When I think about
this boy,
I think about my own kids.

42:23.174 --> 42:24.809 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Again, Ta-Nehisi
Coates:

42:24.842 --> 42:29.614 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TA-NEHISI COATES: The moment he
spoke out,
it completely politicized the
trial.

42:29.647 --> 42:30.982 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
You know what I mean?

42:31.015 --> 42:35.420 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Trayvon became a symbol of
Obamaism, or
something like that.

42:35.453 --> 42:39.190 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Like, it became racialized in a
sort of way.

42:39.223 --> 42:44.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: In 2014, Michael
Brown, another
unarmed black teen, was shot and
killed by

42:44.929 --> 42:46.597 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a Ferguson, Missouri, police
officer.

42:46.631 --> 42:53.571 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A year later, a black man named
Freddie Gray
died in police custody in
Baltimore.

42:53.604 --> 42:59.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in Charleston, South
Carolina, a white
man massacred nine black
parishioners during

42:59.744 --> 43:00.945 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a Bible study.

43:00.978 --> 43:05.049 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA (singing): Amazing
grace, how
sweet the sound.

43:05.082 --> 43:16.260 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

43:16.294 --> 43:20.932 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Jarrett says
these events brought
to the surface racial unease
that already

43:20.965 --> 43:22.433 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
existed.

43:22.467 --> 43:24.135 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VALERIE JARRETT: Those tensions
were there
before we had a video camera.

43:24.168 --> 43:28.139 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We just didn't see them on the
news and in
the social media the way we are
today.

43:28.172 --> 43:33.678 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think a lot of that has
encouraged particularly
young people to come out and
peacefully demonstrate,

43:33.711 --> 43:37.682 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to get involved with their local
government,
to hold them more accountable
than perhaps

43:37.715 --> 43:39.484 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
they were.

43:39.517 --> 43:42.787 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Meanwhile,
President Obama's
Justice Department aggressively
prosecuted

43:42.820 --> 43:44.689 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
civil rights abuses.

43:44.722 --> 43:49.760 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
He highlighted racial
disparities within the
criminal justice system.

43:49.794 --> 43:55.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Mr. Obama spearheaded
initiatives like
My Brother's Keeper, a
mentorship program

43:55.633 --> 43:57.869 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for young men of color.

43:57.902 --> 44:03.174 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But in his farewell speech this
month, the
president acknowledged there was
much left

44:03.207 --> 44:05.009 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to accomplish.

44:05.042 --> 44:09.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA: Race relations are
better than
they were 10, or 20, or 30 years
ago, no matter

44:09.313 --> 44:10.781 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
what some folks say.

44:10.815 --> 44:16.854 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But we're not where we need to
be, and all
of us have more work to do.

44:16.888 --> 44:18.689 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(APPLAUSE)

44:18.723 --> 44:21.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Yesterday, I sat
down yesterday
with three individuals who have
given a lot

44:21.592 --> 44:27.331 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of thought to Mr. Obama's legacy
and his impact
on black Americans.

44:27.365 --> 44:29.400 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We're joined by James Peterson.

44:29.433 --> 44:34.672 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's director of Africana
studies at Lehigh
University and the host of
"Remix."

44:34.705 --> 44:38.175 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's a podcast dedicated to race
and politics.

44:38.209 --> 44:42.246 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Rael Nelson James, she oversees
diversity
work for the Bridgespan Group.

44:42.280 --> 44:46.017 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's anyone profit philanthropic
advisory
firm.

44:46.050 --> 44:51.289 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Sherrilyn Ifill, president
of the NAACP
Legal Defense Fund.

44:51.322 --> 44:53.057 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And we welcome all three of you.

44:53.090 --> 44:55.693 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
James Peterson, how do you look
back on his
presidency overall?

44:55.726 --> 44:57.528 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES PETERSON, Director of
Africana Studies,
Lehigh University: You know,
Folks from my

44:57.562 --> 45:01.999 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
parents' generation couldn't
imagine there
being a black president of the
United States.

45:02.033 --> 45:04.702 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so I think we have to honor
that piece
of it.

45:04.735 --> 45:09.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But for progressive folks, the
substance of
the policies sometimes just
isn't there.

45:09.340 --> 45:15.212 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think, as we sort of
transition into
the next administration, we're
going to be

45:15.246 --> 45:18.549 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
kind of queued up to be very,
very nostalgic
about President Obama.

45:18.583 --> 45:22.653 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we have to understand there
were lots
of challenge, not just based on
obstructionism,

45:22.687 --> 45:26.557 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but based on sort of the kind of
centrist
politics that have dominated
Democratic Party

45:26.591 --> 45:31.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
politics for the last couple of
decades that
President Obama really
represented.

45:31.162 --> 45:33.030 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Sherrilyn Ifill,
what about
that?

45:33.064 --> 45:34.832 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SHERRILYN IFILL, President,
NAACP Legal Defense
and Educational Fund: Well, it's
interesting.

45:34.865 --> 45:38.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I actually think we're going to
need more
time to assess the substantive
record as well.

45:38.269 --> 45:41.672 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think it's kind of hard to
fully assess
it at this moment.

45:41.706 --> 45:45.142 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, when you think about
health care
reform, when you think about one
of the president's

45:45.176 --> 45:49.981 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
first acts was signing the Lilly
Ledbetter
Equal Pay Act for Women, when
you look at

45:50.014 --> 45:54.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the work in the criminal justice
space, which
was largely executed through the
Department

45:55.019 --> 46:00.658 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Justice, but through this
president's Department
of Justice and with his full
support and with

46:00.691 --> 46:05.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
his interest and strong desire,
you look at
the Smart on Crime policies,
ending solitary

46:05.930 --> 46:11.936 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
confinement for juveniles, you
look at his
clemency, he's granted clemency
to more people

46:11.969 --> 46:15.239 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
than any of the 11 presidents
before him combined.

46:15.272 --> 46:19.276 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, the federal system, the
federal prison
system and the federal criminal
justice system,

46:19.310 --> 46:21.679 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is a fraction compared to the
system in the
states.

46:21.712 --> 46:25.750 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the purpose was really to
set an example,
to show what can be done and
what should be

46:25.783 --> 46:28.219 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
done around criminal justice.

46:28.252 --> 46:33.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Same for voting rights and the
effort to really
stand against this effort of
voter suppression

46:33.391 --> 46:35.059 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of African-American voters.

46:35.092 --> 46:39.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Rael Nelson
James, we're
talking about his overall legacy
and what

46:39.997 --> 46:45.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that meant in many instances for
black Americans,
whether it was aimed at
specifically black

46:45.569 --> 46:47.338 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Americans or not.

46:47.371 --> 46:49.807 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RAEL NELSON JAMES, Bridgespan
Group: It's
a tightrope walk to be the first
black person

46:49.840 --> 46:55.379 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
to be in a position,
particularly the presidency,
and to balance what it means to
be the president

46:55.413 --> 47:00.217 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the entire United States, and
what it means
to be black community to see the
first black

47:00.251 --> 47:02.420 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
person as president.

47:02.453 --> 47:09.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what those expectations
were, I felt,
weren't always fair in terms of
what it truly

47:09.160 --> 47:16.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
means to hold that office, and
the kind of
balance that one has to have,
and because,

47:16.233 --> 47:19.970 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as was said, President Obama's a
political
moderate.

47:20.004 --> 47:25.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so those who are on the left
who are truly
progressive, I think, should
have expected

47:25.209 --> 47:28.646 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that he would fall short of
their expectations.

47:28.679 --> 47:41.592 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This sort of desire that he
would speak to
or evangelize a sort of black
community platform

47:41.625 --> 47:48.299 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
above all else, I think, was
sort of an unfair
expectation, though I think we
got at times

47:48.332 --> 47:51.902 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
really strong messages, you
know, about being
black in America.

47:51.936 --> 47:55.005 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: James Peterson,
were the expectations
unfair?

47:55.039 --> 47:59.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES PETERSON: Some of the
expectations were
absolutely unfair, not just from
black America,

47:59.744 --> 48:04.682 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but from white America, and not
just from
those on the left, but from
those on the right.

48:04.715 --> 48:09.153 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He sort of took on the historic
moment, in
a sense that the expectations
for some kind

48:09.186 --> 48:14.492 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of post-racial, utopian,
harmonious society
kind of was on his shoulders,
especially early

48:14.525 --> 48:16.427 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
on in his first term

48:16.460 --> 48:20.030 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think we were disabused of
that notion fairly
early on.

48:20.064 --> 48:22.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think folks came to their
senses a little
bit.

48:22.733 --> 48:26.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But when we -- even if we just
take a look
at his messaging that has been
directed towards

48:26.937 --> 48:32.243 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
African-Americans, too often,
President Obama
trucked in the kind of
discourses that those

48:32.276 --> 48:38.048 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on the right used, in terms of
the behavioral
challenges, or lack thereof,
that sometimes

48:38.082 --> 48:41.852 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people want to hang structural
responsibility
around.

48:41.886 --> 48:48.225 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, he's often sort of
articulating
a narrative of personal
responsibility.

48:48.259 --> 48:52.596 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there's nothing wrong with
personal responsibility,
but all of us are also aware of
the fact that

48:52.630 --> 48:58.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there are structural challenges
in the United
States that have -- are sort of
part of income

48:58.769 --> 49:02.072 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
inequality, part of racial
stratification.

49:02.106 --> 49:07.077 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think it's legitimate for
folks to have
expected President Barack Obama
to speak more

49:07.111 --> 49:11.482 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
strongly about those things,
even in the environment
of obstructionism, even in an
environment

49:11.515 --> 49:16.921 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
where there's a rise of
racialized hate over
the last eight years, based on
the fact that

49:16.954 --> 49:18.722 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
he is the first black president.

49:18.756 --> 49:22.960 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Sherrilyn Ifill,
what about
this notion that he, as James
Peterson just

49:22.993 --> 49:25.830 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
put it, trucked in the language
of those on
the right?

49:25.863 --> 49:29.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SHERRILYN IFILL: Well, I always
wanted more
from this president and
probably...

49:29.099 --> 49:30.868 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And you had many
meetings with
him.

49:30.901 --> 49:34.004 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
SHERRILYN IFILL: In many
meetings with him
around criminal justice reform,
around judicial

49:34.038 --> 49:35.906 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
nominations, around any number
of issues.

49:35.940 --> 49:38.909 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I always wanted more, and
will probably
want more of any president.

49:38.943 --> 49:41.345 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So I'm always pushing a
president to do more.

49:41.378 --> 49:43.147 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Do I think he could have done
more?

49:43.180 --> 49:47.751 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I always went very clearly with
a question
about what was available for the
president

49:47.785 --> 49:52.122 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to do, and within the context of
what he could
do, was he will willing to go up
to the line?

49:52.156 --> 49:55.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think there are some issues in
which he
was doing as much as he possibly
could.

49:56.026 --> 49:57.862 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The headwinds from the right
were unbelievable.

49:57.895 --> 50:02.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so what we might have
wanted, particularly
in the space of legislation,
just couldn't

50:02.733 --> 50:04.668 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
happen with this Congress.

50:04.702 --> 50:06.604 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Rhetorically, it's a whole
'nother story.

50:06.637 --> 50:08.572 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
People wanted to hear what they
wanted to
hear.

50:08.606 --> 50:12.142 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, in many ways, the
president's rhetoric
was precisely what he promised
it would be

50:12.176 --> 50:13.978 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
on the campaign trail.

50:14.011 --> 50:17.114 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think people just didn't want
to hear it,
because many of us put all our
hopes and dreams

50:17.147 --> 50:19.783 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and wishes for this first black
president
into him.

50:19.817 --> 50:24.555 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think he was remarkably
consistent in who
he said he was and what he
believed.

50:24.588 --> 50:27.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And for that, I was grateful,
because I always
felt like I knew who I was
dealing with.

50:27.491 --> 50:31.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
